				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Go to your state labor board.  They will make the company pay her the salary that she was scheduled for.  The company will then need to sue and prove in court fraud and whatnot.
<br />

<br />
The only thing you will need a lawyer for is to defend against their law suit or if you want to sue for wrongful termination which you may or maynot have a case depending on the laws in your state.  For example in California they got this whole "at will" thing.
<br />

<br />
But as for them withholding salary on suspicion and asking for more money, like I said just go to your state labor board.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
