				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>danille wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">It is against the law for them to withold any money she earned.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
It is against the law to steal from your employers.
<br />

<br />
So... she might get her holiday pay etc back... but she will get slapped with a lawsuit and quite possibly have criminal charges filled against her if she pulls an attitude as the company will be advised to involve the police.
<br />

<br />
Good suggestion to get a lawyer... however the approach should be from her (if guilty of course) is to come to some form of agreement of what is owed by who for what.
<br />

<br />
From there she can set up a repayment schedule where the company gets its $$$ back with the minimal amount of fuss.
<br />

<br />
9/10 times a company will choose to avoid criminal preceedings as they are costly not only in the terms of lawyer fees... but the time, effort and energy of the executives and employees who will miss work to give evidence.
<br />

<br />
Of course... if she REALLY wants to spend some time in jail, have a criminal record and STILL have to pay the $$$ back you can listen to the advice of others to bitch to the employment equivilent of the ACLU. 
<br />

<br />
Tell her to kiss her last paycheck goodbye. Its gone. (Well... she already spent it didn't she? Advances remember?)
<br />

<br />
I would suggest a more dipolmatic approach in this instance is required to find out what is owned NET and set up a repayment schedule ASAP.
<br />

